This whole sector in the oil/gas/related stocks have had an excellent run. In
particular the large integrated oils including XOM & CVX and even some of the
smaller companies including MRO and OXY have had excellent gains. I am
generally a long term holder (three to five years) and find your value approach
to buying similar to mine. It's pretty easy to identify out of favor value
oriented companies and then wait until they become in favor to sell. I
accumulate shares over time to establish my long term position.

So here is the question. The hardest decision for me is when to sell and
developing an exit strategy. What alerts you to a sell decision and what type
of approach do you take into consideration when selling? I generally scale my
selling into 1/3 positions and sometimes even use cover calls (selling the
strike month after the x-dividend date) to squeeze out additional profits.

Perhaps you can include in your discussions some of your exit strategies for
value positions you have acquired. I try to find special situations that make a
stock a "value" proposition and when the market discovers this look at selling
part of my position.

Any observations you can provide in determining an appropriate "exit" strategy
would be helpful.

