%BOM---------------------
Date:9/22/2004 1:18:44 AM
From:Paul Senior
Selling is the most difficult part of an investment operation.

Most people sell too soon. I'm guilty of this sometimes too.

For most value situations, I outlook at least a 12- 18 month holding. If
there's a corporate restructuring or transformation, I'm figuring 3-5 years
before results show in the stock. Maybe 5-7 years for completion and top gains
in the stock.

I guess most advisors would say to sell if there's been a change in the
underlying fundamentals or expectations for which the stock was bought. Or if
one sees a new opportunity (stock) that is just so much better than the
currently held stock. (Pig-at-trough investing. I'm not a fan of it.)

Know your personality. I'm a strong 6 - loyalist on the Eneagram circle. Which
means with my nature I might likely stick with a situation or stock longer than
I should. And another danger for me is that I pick the wrong stock and hold it.

http://www.enneagraminstitute.com/eneagram.asp

Here are some ideas I find helpful:

I'm with you in easing out of positions. You use 1/3; I like fifths. Each stock
is different; as long as I can see that management can continue to deliver
results, I generally will hold shares. But if the stock seems expensive on
p/sales and/or p/book I will want to sell at least some.

If I can get people on the thread to offer up a buy or sell decision about one
of my picks, I've found the sell advice to be very helpful. When I can listen
to it and absorb it. (It's often more difficult to convince somebody to sell
something they own than convince them to buy.)

For some stocks I'll have a core position and a trading position.

How about some of you other guys chiming in with an opinion?

My opinion isn't worth that much. Obviously, if I'm a loyalist type and I've
accumulated over 200 different stocks, I'm not one to be giving advice on
selling. -gg-
%EOM----------------------

