Date:9/22/2004 1:00:49 PM
From:E_K_S
That is helpful Paul. I have always learned that you can not be right 100% of
the time and there is nothing wrong with booking a profit and moving on.
Sometimes I have a hard time to sell a position because I have worked so hard
acquiring the "value" position at a good entry point.

One thing I do when I begin to establish an entry point on an investment is I
write down my exit strategy. I might utilize a partial covered call position
where I can lock in my 10% annual return goal and then continue to add to my
position as the story unfolds. Like you, on other special situations, I buy a
very small position as it makes me monitor the company (read their annual
report) and basically pay more attention to the value proposition.

I modify my exit strategy (in writing) over the term of the investment and
modify my structured call position or even use naked puts to acquire more
shares. I use both naked puts and trading stock to take advantage of
significant swings when there is a sell off or unexpected positive news.

The best technical indicator I use for buying is the 20 & 50 day
on-balance-volume average. I want this to be at it's extreme lows as this tells
me that everybody has thrown in the towel (blood in the street concept) and I
can buy for $0.50 on the dollar. I also want the company to be near it's five
year lows especially if it's a 3-5 year turn around story.

The real life stories are helpful as every situation is different.

EKS
