Date:9/22/2004 10:06:45 PM
From:Spekulatius
re Selling stocks -
I found that my sell decisions were much less rational than
my buy decisions in the past. In particular, I had a tendency to pocket
gains and play the volatility game. This has worked sometimes but hurt
my performance, in particular during the long bull market in 2003. From Y2000
to Y2003, the average holding period for my stocks has been around 3-4 month
only, and I did not hold any stock longer 8 month during the period.

I felt discouraged to hold on to stocks a long time due to the bad economy,
corporate scandals and my own unsteady personality. During 2003, I started
to reduce my frantic trading and have now a goal of holding on to stocks for
1-2 years. I order to do so, I changed my selection criteria for the stocks -
instead of focusing on value and potential I decided that "quality" (in terms
of
management integrity, balance sheet, track record etc.) is paramount, since
i find it virtually impossible to hold on stocks when i have lost confidence.

Before investing, I define how much money I am willing to put in a stocks
(based on my risk assessment) and depending on the sum, I buy a small position
at once, or larger position in fractions. Accordingly, I do likewise with my
sells.
My cutoff criteria for a low risk stock is 8% return/year with the assumption
that
the market will increase by 6-7% going forward - for higher risk stocks, i
demand
higher returns. When a stocks approaches approx. market returns (based on NPV
with 6% implied
return) I may start to sell chunks of my holding with consideration of the
technical
condition of the stock (charts).
%EOM----------------------

